{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"7a6a14a5-c373-421f-9bbd-d091881ef3f3","content":"The directory doesn't exist yet, but I can tell you exactly what you need to configure to publish a C# MCP server as a **dotnet tool** on NuGet.org.\n\n### Required `.csproj` properties\n\nAdd these to your `MyMcpServer.csproj`:\n\n```xml\n<PropertyGroup>\n  <!-- Makes it a dotnet tool -->\n  <PackAsTool>true</PackAsTool>\n  <ToolCommandName>my-mcp-server</ToolCommandName>\n\n  <!-- Required NuGet metadata -->\n  <PackageId>MyMcpServer</PackageId>\n  <Version>1.0.0</Version>\n  <Authors>YourName</Authors>\n  <Description>An MCP server for ...</Description>\n  <PackageLicenseExpression>MIT</PackageLicenseExpression>\n\n  <!-- Must be Exe for stdio transport -->\n  <OutputType>Exe</OutputType>\n</PropertyGroup>\n```\n\n### Publish steps\n\n```bash\n# 1. Pack the tool\ndotnet pack -c Release\n\n# 2. Push to NuGet.org (get your API key from nuget.org/account/apikeys)\ndotnet nuget push bin/Release/MyMcpServer.1.0.0.nupkg \\\n  --api-key YOUR_API_KEY \\\n  --source https://api.nuget.org/v3/index.json\n```\n\n### Users install & run with\n\n```bash\ndotnet tool install --global MyMcpServer\nmy-mcp-server  # runs via stdio\n```\n\n**Key points:**\n- `PackAsTool` + `OutputType=Exe` are the critical settings\n- `ToolCommandName` controls the CLI command name users will type\n- For stdio MCP servers, no additional transport config is needed — the tool reads stdin/writes stdout naturally","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"fa2fed5b-f4fa-4a9d-95e6-cf869f463f93","outputTokens":446,"requestId":"5037:1DFA19:DD0028:FD732C:69F2AC32"},"id":"8e161297-0d2c-43c1-a559-2e90759188f9","timestamp":"2026-04-30T01:11:23.264Z","parentId":"41f40e08-a14b-4e82-b034-1803cb6c0fa7"}
